  <body>
    <h1>Namma-Skill Product Requirements Document</h1>
    <p class="meta">
      <strong>Project:</strong> Namma-Skill Web and Android Skill Development Course Tracker<br />
      <strong>Document Type:</strong> Product Requirements Document<br />
      <strong>Prepared For:</strong> Academic project submission and demo evaluation<br />
      <strong>Version:</strong> 1.0
    </p>

    <h2>1. Product Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Namma-Skill is a web and Android-based skill development course tracker designed to help rural
      and small-town youth discover nearby government training opportunities. The platform allows
      candidates to search courses, filter by trade or duration, view training center information,
      apply for a course, and generate a structured candidate summary for the training center.
    </p>

    <h2>2. Problem Statement</h2>
    <p>
      Many rural youth miss government skill development opportunities because batch information is
      often shared through notice boards, local announcements, or center-level communication. This
      creates an information gap between candidates and training centers. Candidates do not have a
      simple centralized system to discover upcoming batches, check eligibility, view seats, or apply
      quickly. Namma-Skill solves this by providing a simple digital course discovery and application
      workflow.
    </p>

    <h2>3. Product Goals</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Help candidates discover nearby government skill development courses.</li>
      <li>Allow users to filter courses by trade and duration.</li>
      <li>Display important course details such as eligibility, seats, stipend, and placement support.</li>
      <li>Enable candidates to apply for courses through a simple form.</li>
      <li>Generate a candidate summary that can be used by training centers for follow-up.</li>
      <li>Store submitted applications locally for demonstration and review.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>4. Target Users</h2>
    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>User Type</th>
        <th>Description</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Rural Youth</td>
        <td>Candidates looking for job-ready vocational training and self-employment opportunities.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Students</td>
        <td>Students who have completed school or college and want practical skills.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Unemployed Candidates</td>
        <td>Users searching for nearby courses that can improve employment chances.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Training Centers</td>
        <td>Government skill centers that need structured candidate interest and application details.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>5. Scope</h2>
    <h3>In Scope</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Course discovery interface.</li>
      <li>Search and filtering by trade, title, center, short-term, and long-term duration.</li>
      <li>Nearby training center display.</li>
      <li>Candidate application form.</li>
      <li>Candidate summary generation.</li>
      <li>Local saved application history.</li>
      <li>Web version using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.</li>
      <li>Kotlin Android version using native Android views and SharedPreferences.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Out of Scope for Current Version</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Real backend database.</li>
      <li>Authentication for candidates or training centers.</li>
      <li>Real GPS location tracking.</li>
      <li>Real SMS, WhatsApp, or push notifications.</li>
      <li>Online payment or certificate verification.</li>
      <li>Admin dashboard for adding live batches.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>6. Key Features</h2>
    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Feature</th>
        <th>Description</th>
        <th>Priority</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Course Listing</td>
        <td>Shows available vocational courses with trade, duration, center, eligibility, seats, stipend, and support details.</td>
        <td>High</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Search</td>
        <td>Allows users to search by course title, trade, or center name.</td>
        <td>High</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Filters</td>
        <td>Allows filtering by Electrician, Sewing, Coding, Mobile Repair, Welding, Short term, and Long term.</td>
        <td>High</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Alert Me</td>
        <td>Simulates saving interest in a selected trade for batch alerts.</td>
        <td>Medium</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Apply</td>
        <td>Lets the candidate select a course and fill out application details.</td>
        <td>High</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Candidate Summary</td>
        <td>Generates a structured summary for trainer callback and document verification.</td>
        <td>High</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Saved Applications</td>
        <td>Stores submitted applications locally for demo and review.</td>
        <td>Medium</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>7. Functional Requirements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The system shall display a list of available training courses.</li>
      <li>The system shall allow users to search courses by title, trade, or center.</li>
      <li>The system shall allow users to filter courses by trade and duration.</li>
      <li>The system shall allow users to select a course for application.</li>
      <li>The system shall collect candidate name, phone number, village, education, and motivation.</li>
      <li>The system shall validate required application fields.</li>
      <li>The system shall generate a candidate summary after submission.</li>
      <li>The system shall save submitted applications locally.</li>
      <li>The system shall allow users to view saved application summaries.</li>
      <li>The system shall allow users to copy or clear saved summaries.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>8. Non-Functional Requirements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The interface should be simple, clean, and easy to understand.</li>
      <li>The application should work without a backend for demo purposes.</li>
      <li>The web version should run in a modern browser.</li>
      <li>The Android version should run on Android devices with minimum SDK 23 or above.</li>
      <li>The app should use local storage safely for demo data.</li>
      <li>The design should be mobile-friendly and suitable for academic evaluation.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>9. User Flow</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>User opens the Namma-Skill application.</li>
      <li>User browses available training courses.</li>
      <li>User searches or filters courses by trade, center, or duration.</li>
      <li>User selects a course and reviews eligibility, seats, stipend, and support.</li>
      <li>User optionally activates an alert for a trade.</li>
      <li>User fills the candidate application form.</li>
      <li>User submits the form.</li>
      <li>System generates a candidate summary.</li>
      <li>System saves the application locally.</li>
      <li>User can view, copy, or clear saved application data.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>10. Technology Stack</h2>
    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Layer</th>
        <th>Technology</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Web Frontend</td>
        <td>HTML, CSS, JavaScript</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Web Storage</td>
        <td>Browser LocalStorage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Android App</td>
        <td>Kotlin, Android SDK, Native Android Views</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Android Storage</td>
        <td>SharedPreferences</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Build Tool</td>
        <td>Gradle, Android Studio</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>11. Data Model</h2>
    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Entity</th>
        <th>Fields</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Course</td>
        <td>id, title, trade, duration, center, eligibility, seats, stipend, placement</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Candidate</td>
        <td>name, phone, village, education, motivation</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Application</td>
        <td>savedAt, selected course, candidate details, generated summary</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>12. Success Metrics</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>User can find a suitable course in less than one minute.</li>
      <li>User can submit a demo application successfully.</li>
      <li>Training center receives a clear candidate summary.</li>
      <li>Application data persists locally after page refresh or app restart.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>13. Risks and Limitations</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Current version does not use a real backend.</li>
      <li>Course and center data are static demo data.</li>
      <li>Notifications are simulated.</li>
      <li>Local storage is not suitable for production multi-device sync.</li>
      <li>Admin dashboard is not included in the current version.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>14. Future Enhancements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Add Firebase, Supabase, PostgreSQL, or MySQL backend.</li>
      <li>Add admin login for training centers.</li>
      <li>Add real SMS, WhatsApp, or push notifications.</li>
      <li>Add GPS-based center locator.</li>
      <li>Add multilingual support for Kannada, Hindi, and English.</li>
      <li>Add document upload for ID proof and education certificate.</li>
      <li>Add AI-based course recommendation from candidate profile.</li>
      <li>Deploy the web application online.</li>
      <li>Publish signed Android APK or Android App Bundle.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>15. Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      Namma-Skill provides a practical digital solution for connecting rural youth with nearby skill
      development opportunities. The current web and Kotlin Android versions demonstrate course
      discovery, filtering, application submission, candidate summary generation, and local saved
      history. The project is suitable for academic demonstration and can be expanded into a production
      platform with backend, authentication, live data, and notification support.
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
